snippet.textDisplay: I'd like to help with some knowledge I have on the subject. First it looks like you did a pretty decent job with the setup you had, good job. Second, you do not want to blend that. I grew up working with my dad who is a professional bodyman. If you blend into that door it will look worse, and instead of looking like you robbed parts off a similar truck it will look like someone tried to make the wrong color work (because that's whats happening). Its a 2019 you want it to look as new as it is. Here's what you do. 1. Go to an actual paint shop and match the color based on paint chips and have them mix it. 2. Wet sand (yes even into the back door and hood, plan on blending even with the new color). Cover up everything with plastic sheeting except back door, front door, fender and hood.  Prep repaint and clear. And if you feel particularly froggy, wet sand with high (1500 up to 3000) grit sand paper and buff and polish. It'll sine like new money.
snippet.textOriginal: I'd like to help with some knowledge I have on the subject. First it looks like you did a pretty decent job with the setup you had, good job. Second, you do not want to blend that. I grew up working with my dad who is a professional bodyman. If you blend into that door it will look worse, and instead of looking like you robbed parts off a similar truck it will look like someone tried to make the wrong color work (because that's whats happening). Its a 2019 you want it to look as new as it is. Here's what you do. 1. Go to an actual paint shop and match the color based on paint chips and have them mix it. 2. Wet sand (yes even into the back door and hood, plan on blending even with the new color). Cover up everything with plastic sheeting except back door, front door, fender and hood.  Prep repaint and clear. And if you feel particularly froggy, wet sand with high (1500 up to 3000) grit sand paper and buff and polish. It'll sine like new money.

snippet.textDisplay: Hey Wes,  PR4 Needs a G2 undercoat (very light grey) looks like you used a G6 (dark grey undercoat). That would be why your color doesn't look like the paint chip you saw at napa. Remember when you repaint it you must spray a G2 undercoat before you add more red or you will never get the color to match even if you blend.
